1
00:00:02,240 --> 00:00:05,040
[♪]

2
00:00:10,320 --> 00:00:14,440
The golden age of ballooning
can be said to begin
in 1783...

3
00:00:14,560 --> 00:00:16,040
[METAL CLANGING]

4
00:00:16,160 --> 00:00:18,440
...when the Montgolfier
brothers made their
first ascent

5
00:00:18,560 --> 00:00:20,440
in a fire balloon.

6
00:00:20,560 --> 00:00:22,360
On the eve of that--

7
00:00:22,480 --> 00:00:24,240
Come on, come on.

8
00:00:24,360 --> 00:00:26,480
--momentous ascent,
the brothers

9
00:00:26,600 --> 00:00:28,400
took one last look
at their craft

10
00:00:28,520 --> 00:00:31,800
as it stood on the fields
of Annencay.

11
00:00:31,920 --> 00:00:34,560
This is a great moment
for us, Joseph.

12
00:00:34,680 --> 00:00:36,840
It is a great moment
for France.

13
00:00:36,960 --> 00:00:38,440
Ah,<i> oui.</i>

14
00:00:38,560 --> 00:00:40,160
The first ascent
in a hot-air balloon

15
00:00:40,280 --> 00:00:43,960
by the Montgolfier
brothers, 1783.

16
00:00:44,080 --> 00:00:45,920
I can see us now...

17
00:00:46,040 --> 00:00:49,160
just after Montesquieu
and just before Mozart.

18
00:00:49,280 --> 00:00:52,040
I think I'll go and wash.
Good luck.

19
00:00:52,160 --> 00:00:54,560
Oh, it's quite easy really.
I just slap a little
water on--

20
00:00:54,680 --> 00:00:57,120
No, no, no, no.
Good luck for tomorrow.

21
00:00:57,240 --> 00:00:59,960
Oh, I see.
Yes. You too.

22
00:01:00,080 --> 00:01:01,560
Yours has been
the work.

23
00:01:01,680 --> 00:01:05,480
Let us hope
for a safe ascent.

24
00:01:05,600 --> 00:01:07,280
And, uh, don't use
my flannel.

25
00:01:07,400 --> 00:01:11,480
You know...when you showed me
the plans in Paris,

26
00:01:11,600 --> 00:01:13,520
I could not believe
that we should be

27
00:01:13,640 --> 00:01:15,040
the first men
who would fly.

28
00:01:15,160 --> 00:01:16,760
Yes, it's wonderful.

29
00:01:16,880 --> 00:01:19,800
I'm so excited
I could hardly wash.

30
00:01:19,920 --> 00:01:23,200
Yes. I, too, have had
some difficulty washing

31
00:01:23,320 --> 00:01:25,960
these past few days.

32
00:01:26,080 --> 00:01:28,040
Still, what is washing,
when we are on the verge

33
00:01:28,160 --> 00:01:29,760
of a great scientific
breakthrough?

34
00:01:29,880 --> 00:01:32,280
Jacques?
Yes, Joseph?

35
00:01:32,400 --> 00:01:35,560
I've not been washing
very thoroughly

36
00:01:35,680 --> 00:01:37,480
for many years now.

37
00:01:37,600 --> 00:01:39,080
What do you mean?

38
00:01:39,200 --> 00:01:40,800
Y-you must have been
washing your face.

39
00:01:40,920 --> 00:01:43,520
Oh, yes, my face.
I've washed my face.

40
00:01:43,640 --> 00:01:44,840
But my legs...

41
00:01:44,960 --> 00:01:47,320
my stomach, my chest...

42
00:01:47,440 --> 00:01:49,040
they're filthy.

43
00:01:49,160 --> 00:01:52,520
Well, uh, I don't wash
my stomach every day.

44
00:01:52,640 --> 00:01:54,400
Ah, but you wash
far more than me.

45
00:01:54,520 --> 00:01:57,320
You are the cleaner
of the Montgolfier brothers.

46
00:01:57,440 --> 00:01:58,720
This is nothing,
Joseph--

47
00:01:58,840 --> 00:02:00,200
Monsieur
Montgolfier,

48
00:02:00,320 --> 00:02:02,680
a Mr. Parfitt
to see you, sir.

49
00:02:02,800 --> 00:02:04,440
Eh, ah, no, no, no.
Uh, Bartlett.

50
00:02:04,560 --> 00:02:07,000
A Mr. Barklit
to see you, sir.

51
00:02:07,120 --> 00:02:09,920
No. Bart-lett.
With a T.

52
00:02:10,040 --> 00:02:13,520
A Mr. Barrat-elett
to see you, sir.

53
00:02:13,640 --> 00:02:15,440
Bartlett.
Barkit.

54
00:02:15,560 --> 00:02:18,160
Bartlett.
Barklit.

55
00:02:18,280 --> 00:02:19,680
Bartlett.

56
00:02:19,800 --> 00:02:22,760
A Mr. Bart-lett
to see you, sir.

57
00:02:22,880 --> 00:02:25,720
I don't wanna see anyone,
O'Toole. Tell him to go away.

58
00:02:25,840 --> 00:02:28,040
Thank you, sir.

59
00:02:28,160 --> 00:02:29,760
Well, it's
getting late.

60
00:02:29,880 --> 00:02:31,360
I must go
and have a wash.

61
00:02:31,480 --> 00:02:33,440
Uh, what will you be washing?

62
00:02:33,560 --> 00:02:34,960
Oh, just my face and neck.

63
00:02:35,080 --> 00:02:37,040
Perhaps my feet, and
possibly--

64
00:02:37,160 --> 00:02:38,400
But no. No.

65
00:02:38,520 --> 00:02:39,960
Lock up the plans,
Joseph.

66
00:02:40,080 --> 00:02:42,600
Tomorrow they will make us
the toast of France.

67
00:02:42,720 --> 00:02:44,600
The first ascent by
the Montgolfier brothers

68
00:02:44,720 --> 00:02:46,120
in a balloon.

69
00:02:46,240 --> 00:02:49,080
Just after Ballcock
and just before Bang.

70
00:02:49,200 --> 00:02:50,600
What a position.

71
00:02:50,720 --> 00:02:53,040
ANNOUNCER:
<i>So on June 7th, 1783,</i>

72
00:02:53,160 --> 00:02:56,440
<i>the Montgolfier brothers</i>
<i>had a really good wash.</i>

73
00:02:56,560 --> 00:02:58,400
<i>Starting on his face</i>
<i>and arms,</i>

74
00:02:58,520 --> 00:03:01,920
<i>Joseph Michel Montgolfier</i>
<i>went on to scrub his torso,</i>

75
00:03:02,040 --> 00:03:03,960
<i>his legs and his naughty</i>
<i>bits,</i>

76
00:03:04,080 --> 00:03:06,320
<i>before rinsing his whole</i>
<i>body.</i>

77
00:03:06,440 --> 00:03:07,880
<i>That June night,</i>

78
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:09,240
<i>he and his brother between</i>
<i>them</i>

79
00:03:09,360 --> 00:03:12,080
<i>washed 17 square feet</i>
<i>of body area.</i>

80
00:03:12,200 --> 00:03:14,840
<i>They used a kilo and a half</i>
<i>of carbolic soap</i>

81
00:03:14,960 --> 00:03:17,800
<i>and nearly 14 gallons</i>
<i>of nice hot water.</i>

82
00:03:17,920 --> 00:03:21,240
<i>It was indeed</i>
<i>an impressive sight.</i>

83
00:03:21,360 --> 00:03:23,760
<i>Next week on</i>
The Golden Age of Ballooning,

84
00:03:23,880 --> 00:03:25,880
<i>we examine the work</i>
<i>of Glashire and Coxwell,</i>

85
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:28,040
<i>the English balloonists</i>
<i>who ascended to a height</i>

86
00:03:28,160 --> 00:03:31,400
<i>of seven miles in 1862</i>
<i>without washing.</i>

87
00:03:31,520 --> 00:03:34,240
<i>There is also a book called</i>
The Golden Age of Ballooning

88
00:03:34,360 --> 00:03:36,720
<i>published by the BBC</i>
<i>to coincide with the series.</i>

89
00:03:36,840 --> 00:03:38,960
<i>It's in an attractive</i>
<i>hand-tooled binding,</i>

90
00:03:39,080 --> 00:03:41,000
<i>Is priced 5 pounds,</i>
<i>Is priced 5 pounds,</i>

91
00:03:41,120 --> 00:03:43,080
<i>and failure to buy it will make</i>
<i>you liable to a 50 pound fine</i>

92
00:03:43,200 --> 00:03:44,800
<i>or three months in prison.</i>

93
00:03:44,920 --> 00:03:46,840
<i>There's also a record</i>
<i>of someone</i>

94
00:03:46,960 --> 00:03:50,080
<i>reading the book of</i>
The Golden Age of Ballooning,

95
00:03:50,200 --> 00:03:52,560
<i>a crochet-work bedspread</i>
<i>with the words</i>

96
00:03:52,680 --> 00:03:54,160
<i>"The Golden Age of</i>
<i>Ballooning" on it,</i>

97
00:03:54,280 --> 00:03:56,280
<i>available from the BBC,</i>
<i>price 18 pound,</i>

98
00:03:56,400 --> 00:03:57,960
<i>or five months imprisonment.</i>

99
00:03:58,080 --> 00:03:59,840
<i>And there are matching</i>
<i>toilet-seat covers</i>

100
00:03:59,960 --> 00:04:01,520
<i>and courtesy mats</i>
<i>with illustrations</i>

101
00:04:01,640 --> 00:04:04,840
<i>of many of</i>
<i>the balloons mentioned.</i>

102
00:04:04,960 --> 00:04:07,520
<i>Also available is</i>
<i>a life-sized model frog</i>

103
00:04:07,640 --> 00:04:10,160
<i>which croaks the words:</i>
<i>"Golden Age of Ballooning,"</i>

104
00:04:10,280 --> 00:04:12,080
<i>and an attractive</i>
<i>Bakelite case</i>

105
00:04:12,200 --> 00:04:14,640
<i>for storing motorway</i>
<i>construction plans in,</i>

106
00:04:14,760 --> 00:04:17,000
<i>made in the shape of a</i>
<i>balloon.</i>

107
00:04:17,120 --> 00:04:19,680
<i>And now, another chance</i>
<i>to see episode two</i>

108
00:04:19,800 --> 00:04:22,880
<i>of the award-winning series</i>
The Golden Age of Ballooning.

109
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:25,360
[♪]

110
00:04:33,400 --> 00:04:37,480
Oh, Joseph. All you
think about is balloons.

111
00:04:37,600 --> 00:04:40,080
All you talk about
is balloons.

112
00:04:40,200 --> 00:04:43,960
Your beautiful house is full
of bits and pieces of
balloons.

113
00:04:44,080 --> 00:04:45,920
Your books are
all about balloons.

114
00:04:46,040 --> 00:04:47,560
Every time
you sing a song,

115
00:04:47,680 --> 00:04:50,640
it is in some way obliquely
connected with balloons.

116
00:04:50,760 --> 00:04:52,280
Everything you eat

117
00:04:52,400 --> 00:04:55,360
has to have the word "balloon"
incorporated in the title.

118
00:04:55,480 --> 00:04:58,240
Your dogs are
all called Balloon-o.

119
00:04:58,360 --> 00:05:00,520
You tie balloons to your
ankles in the evenings.

120
00:05:00,640 --> 00:05:02,480
I don't do that.

121
00:05:02,600 --> 00:05:05,640
Well...no,
you don't do that.

122
00:05:05,760 --> 00:05:08,080
But you do duck down
and shout:

123
00:05:08,200 --> 00:05:12,280
"Hey, balloons,"
when there are none about.

124
00:05:12,400 --> 00:05:13,920
Oh, your whole life
is becoming

125
00:05:14,040 --> 00:05:15,920
obsessively balloonic,
you know?

126
00:05:16,040 --> 00:05:18,280
Ohh! Why do I
have to hang

127
00:05:18,400 --> 00:05:20,960
from this bloody gasbag
all day?

128
00:05:21,080 --> 00:05:22,800
Don't I mean
anything to you?

129
00:05:22,920 --> 00:05:25,200
Oh,<i> ma chérie,</i>
you mean more to me

130
00:05:25,320 --> 00:05:26,840
than any heavier-than-air
dirigible.

131
00:05:26,960 --> 00:05:29,240
Oh, there you go again!
Don't waggle!

132
00:05:29,360 --> 00:05:31,440
Oh.
I've run your bath
for you, Joseph.

133
00:05:31,560 --> 00:05:33,600
Uh, oh, I'm so sorry,
I didn't realize, uh...

134
00:05:33,720 --> 00:05:37,760
It's all right.
We've done the difficult bit.

135
00:05:37,880 --> 00:05:39,800
Don't forget
we have our special guest

136
00:05:39,920 --> 00:05:41,800
coming this evening.
Oh?

137
00:05:41,920 --> 00:05:43,720
Don't tell me
you've forgotten already.

138
00:05:43,840 --> 00:05:45,280
The man who is giving us

139
00:05:45,400 --> 00:05:46,560
thousands of francs
for experiments.

140
00:05:46,680 --> 00:05:48,840
What man?
Louis XIV.

141
00:05:48,960 --> 00:05:50,400
Isn't he dead?

142
00:05:50,520 --> 00:05:52,200
Evidently not.

143
00:05:52,320 --> 00:05:54,600
All right, I'll be round.

144
00:05:54,720 --> 00:05:56,040
Oh, and Joseph?

145
00:05:56,160 --> 00:05:57,240
Yes, Jacques?

146
00:05:57,360 --> 00:05:59,320
You will...wash, won't you?

147
00:05:59,440 --> 00:06:01,800
Yes, of course.

148
00:06:03,160 --> 00:06:04,680
<i>[DOOR OPENS]</i>

149
00:06:04,800 --> 00:06:08,440
His Royal Majesty
Louis XIV of France.

150
00:06:08,560 --> 00:06:09,560
And
Mr. Bartlett.

151
00:06:09,680 --> 00:06:11,640
[♪]

152
00:06:16,880 --> 00:06:18,600
Your Majesty,
it is a great privilege.

153
00:06:18,720 --> 00:06:20,800
Welcome to our humble abode.

154
00:06:20,920 --> 00:06:23,480
It's, eh, very nice
to be here.

155
00:06:25,600 --> 00:06:27,000
O'Toole.
<i>O'TOOLE: Sir?</i>

156
00:06:27,120 --> 00:06:29,280
Claret for
His Majesty, please.

157
00:06:29,400 --> 00:06:31,960
There's a Mr. Bartlett
outside again, sir.

158
00:06:32,080 --> 00:06:34,080
Not now. We have
the king of France here.

159
00:06:34,200 --> 00:06:35,440
Yes, sir.

160
00:06:38,080 --> 00:06:39,280
Hm.

161
00:06:41,520 --> 00:06:43,120
[EXHALES]

162
00:06:45,480 --> 00:06:47,400
[CLEARS THROAT]

163
00:06:56,160 --> 00:06:58,560
Your Majesty, you had a--
A pleasant journey, I trust?

164
00:06:58,680 --> 00:07:01,040
Yes, yes. Oh, definitely,
yes, yes.

165
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:05,840
Oh, aye. Aye. Mm.

166
00:07:11,760 --> 00:07:13,120
You have come from Paris?

167
00:07:13,240 --> 00:07:15,000
Where?

168
00:07:15,120 --> 00:07:17,280
Eh, from Paris?
You have traveled from Paris?

169
00:07:17,400 --> 00:07:20,160
Oh, yes, yes, yes. We've come
from, eh-- From, uh, Paris.

170
00:07:20,280 --> 00:07:23,240
Yes, oh, yes. Yes, we've, uh,
just come from, eh...

171
00:07:23,360 --> 00:07:25,560
Eh...Paris, yes.

172
00:07:26,640 --> 00:07:28,400
O'TOOLE: Sir?
Yes, O'Toole?

173
00:07:28,520 --> 00:07:30,680
Which one is
the claret, sir?

174
00:07:30,800 --> 00:07:32,720
The claret
is in the decanter.

175
00:07:32,840 --> 00:07:34,080
The wooden thing?

176
00:07:34,200 --> 00:07:36,080
No, no.
The glass thing.

177
00:07:36,200 --> 00:07:38,480
The glass decanter
with the round glass stopper.

178
00:07:38,600 --> 00:07:40,000
Oh, yes, behind the door.

179
00:07:40,120 --> 00:07:42,320
No, no.
On the sideboard.

180
00:07:42,440 --> 00:07:43,800
The sideboard?

181
00:07:43,920 --> 00:07:45,800
The sideboard, yes.

182
00:07:48,720 --> 00:07:50,840
Look, you go into
the<i> salle à manger --</i>

183
00:07:50,960 --> 00:07:52,760
the dining room, right?

184
00:07:52,880 --> 00:07:55,840
--and the sideboard's
on your left by the wall.

185
00:07:55,960 --> 00:07:57,560
Beside the master's
portrait.

186
00:07:57,680 --> 00:07:59,920
Oh. Above
the mirror, sir?

187
00:08:00,040 --> 00:08:02,080
No, no, no, no. The mirror's
on the other side.

188
00:08:02,200 --> 00:08:03,680
It's opposite the mirror.

189
00:08:03,800 --> 00:08:05,520
But that's
the table, sir.

190
00:08:05,640 --> 00:08:07,440
No, you don't go as far
as the table. Oh, look--

191
00:08:07,560 --> 00:08:09,160
You go into
the room, right?

192
00:08:09,280 --> 00:08:11,280
On your right is the door
to the orangery,

193
00:08:11,400 --> 00:08:13,640
straight ahead of you
is the door to the library,

194
00:08:13,760 --> 00:08:16,320
and to your left...
is the sideboard.

195
00:08:16,440 --> 00:08:18,440
Ah, yes, I see, sir.

196
00:08:20,200 --> 00:08:23,040
And the claret is on top
of the sideboard, to the left.

197
00:08:23,160 --> 00:08:25,480
On the left.
Yes.

198
00:08:25,600 --> 00:08:28,360
As one looks at it, sir?
Yes.

199
00:08:28,480 --> 00:08:30,520
I see, sir. Thank you.

200
00:08:30,640 --> 00:08:32,520
O'Toole.
Yes, sir.

201
00:08:32,640 --> 00:08:34,400
Will you please tell Monsieur
Joseph our guest is here.

202
00:08:34,520 --> 00:08:36,120
Yes, sir.

203
00:08:37,400 --> 00:08:38,880
[WHISPERING INDISTINCTLY]

204
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:40,360
Ah!

205
00:08:40,480 --> 00:08:42,440
I'm, uh, sorry
about that, Your Majesty.

206
00:08:42,560 --> 00:08:45,160
[SPEAKS FRENCH]

207
00:08:45,280 --> 00:08:47,760
Apparently, sir, there's
a plan to build a canal

208
00:08:47,880 --> 00:08:50,920
between the two Egyptian--
Not now, O'Toole.

209
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:54,960
Well, eh,
Mr. Montgolfier,

210
00:08:55,080 --> 00:08:56,760
let's not beat
around the bush.

211
00:08:56,880 --> 00:08:58,840
My, eh-- My-- My dukes and I
are very busy men.

212
00:08:58,960 --> 00:09:01,200
What we'd like to do
is see the, uh, plans

213
00:09:01,320 --> 00:09:03,960
of your proposed balloon,
if that's at all possible.

214
00:09:04,080 --> 00:09:05,840
Certainly. I have them
here ready prepared.

215
00:09:05,960 --> 00:09:08,080
Oh, great, hen.
Now, what we'd like to do

216
00:09:08,200 --> 00:09:10,520
is, eh...take these,
uh, back with us

217
00:09:10,640 --> 00:09:12,320
for the Royal Archives
of, eh--

218
00:09:12,440 --> 00:09:14,160
France.
France, aye.

219
00:09:14,280 --> 00:09:16,760
Well, it is indeed a great
honor that I cannot refuse.

220
00:09:16,880 --> 00:09:18,160
Right. Okay,
let's get 'em.

221
00:09:18,280 --> 00:09:21,840
JOSEPH: Just a moment!
JACQUES: Joseph.

222
00:09:21,960 --> 00:09:24,960
That man is not Louis XIV.

223
00:09:25,080 --> 00:09:26,880
Joseph, are you
out of your mind?

224
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:28,360
I've been looking it up
in my bath.

225
00:09:28,480 --> 00:09:31,800
Louis XIV died in 1717.

226
00:09:31,920 --> 00:09:35,200
It's now 1783.
Answer me that.

227
00:09:35,320 --> 00:09:36,800
Did I say Louis XIV?

228
00:09:36,920 --> 00:09:40,280
I'm sorry, I meant Louis XV.
Louis XV.

229
00:09:40,400 --> 00:09:42,920
He died in 1774.

230
00:09:43,040 --> 00:09:45,280
All right.

231
00:09:45,400 --> 00:09:47,400
Louis XVI.

232
00:09:47,520 --> 00:09:50,240
Listen to me,
smart-arse...

233
00:09:50,360 --> 00:09:51,960
when you're king
of France,

234
00:09:52,080 --> 00:09:54,880
you've got better things to do
than go around all day

235
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:56,960
remembering
your bloody number.

236
00:09:57,080 --> 00:09:59,000
[BONES SNAP,
GRUNTING]

237
00:09:59,120 --> 00:10:00,920
All right. You wanna
argue about numbers?
No, no.

238
00:10:01,040 --> 00:10:02,720
Boys, get hold of these plans
for the Royal Archives.

